05642nam a22006495i 9780773566415DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735664157 a10.1515/97807735664152doi  a(DE-B1597)655276  a(OCoLC)1394871815  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJX1395bR57 1997eb 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a3271 aLe Prestre, Philippe G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRole Quests in the Post-Cold War Era :bForeign Policies in Transition /cPhilippe G. Le Prestre. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tTables -- tAcknowledgments -- tAuthor! Author! Defining Foreign Policy Roles after the Cold War -- tThe Soviet Union/Russia: Which Past for Which Future? -- tArticulating the New International Role of the United States during Previous Transitions, 1916–1919, 1943–1947 -- tThe United States: An Elusive Role Quest after the Cold War -- tJapan: A Great Power Despite Itself -- tGermany: To Be or Not to Be Normal? -- tFrance: The Strait jacket of New Freedom -- tGreat Britain: Still Searching for Status? -- tChina: Role Conceptions after the Cold War -- tCanada: A Reassertion of Its Role as a Middle Power -- tChange and Continuity in Foreign Policy Role Conceptions after the Cold War -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tCentre d’études des politiques étrangères et de sécurité Université du Québec á Montréal0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA state's articulation of its national role betrays its preferences and an image of the world, triggers expectations, and influences the definition of the situation and of available options. Extending Kal Holsti's early work on the usefulness of the concept of role, Role Quests in the Post-Cold War Era examines the nature, evolution, and origins of role conceptions, key aspects largely ignored in a literature obsessed with the quest for immediate relevance. For each country contributors present the major foreign policy debate that took place at the end of the Cold War and examine, through an analysis of major speeches, the relative weight of identity and international status in the definition of the national role. Uncovering the different roles that states claim for themselves allows reflection on the possibility of international cooperation in the maintenance of international order. This study helps assess the importance of identity in national role conceptions, identify potential conflicts arising from the clash of roles masquerading as interests, and clarifies existing contradictions in prevailing roles. Contributors include Caroline Alain, Onnig Beylérian, Christophe Canivet, Jean-René Chotard, André Donneur, Philippe G. Le Prestre, Paul Létourneau, Jacques Lévesque, Alexander Macleod, Marie-Elisabeth Räkel, Jean-François Thibeault, and Charles Thumerelle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlain, Caroline C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeylerian, Onnig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCanivet, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChotard, Jean-Rene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonneur, André P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLétourneau, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLévesque, Jacques, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacleod